,"pos":[29736,29754]},{"content":"Cocos2d-x programmer's guide","pos":[29819,29847]},{"content":"Cocos2d-x Programmers Guide v3.8","pos":[29866,29898]},{"content":"Cocos2d-x on Windows 10 (blog post)","pos":[29980,30015]},{"content":"Running Cocos2d-x on Windows 10","pos":[30034,30065]},{"content":"Cocos2d-x Windows Store games (video)","pos":[30187,30224]},{"content":"Build a Game with Cocos2d-x for Windows Devices","pos":[30243,30290]},{"content":"Unreal Engine","pos":[30427,30440]},{"content":"Unreal Engine 4 is a complete suite of game development tools for all types of games and developers.","pos":[30442,30542]},{"content":"For the most demanding console and PC games, Unreal Engine is used by game developers worldwide.","pos":[30543,30639]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>DirectX 12 early access program<ept id=\"p1\">](#dxeap)</ept> members who subscribe to Unreal Engine 4 can receive access to an Unreal Engine 4.4 development project that supports DirectX 12.","pos":[30640,30811]},{"content":"Unreal Engine overview","pos":[30921,30943]},{"content":"What is Unreal Engine 4","pos":[30962,30985]},{"content":"Middleware and partners","pos":[31072,31095]},{"content":"There are many other middleware and engine partners that can provide solutions depending on your game development needs.","pos":[31097,31217]},{"content":"Windows Dev Center gaming partners","pos":[31327,31361]},{"content":"Dev Center Partners (Gaming)","pos":[31380,31408]},{"content":"Windows Dev Center partners","pos":[31509,31536]},{"content":"Dev Center Partners","pos":[31555,31574]},{"content":"Porting your game","pos":[31656,31673]},{"content":"If you have an existing game, there are many resources and guides available to help you quickly bring your game to the UWP.","pos":[31675,31798]},{"content":"To jumpstart your porting efforts, you might also consider using a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Universal Windows Platform Bridge<ept id=\"p1\">](#uwp_bridges)</ept>.","pos":[31799,31916]},{"content":"Porting a Windows 8 app to a Universal Windows Platform app","pos":[32026,32085]},{"content":"Move from Windows Runtime 8.x to UWP","pos":[32104,32140]},{"content":"Porting a Windows 8 app to a Universal Windows Platform app (video)","pos":[32236,32303]},{"content":"Porting 8.1 Apps to Windows 10","pos":[32322,32352]},{"content":"Porting an iOS app to a Universal Windows Platform app","pos":[32460,32514]},{"content":"Move from iOS to UWP","pos":[32533,32553]},{"content":"Porting a Silverlight app to a Universal Windows Platform app","pos":[32649,32710]},{"content":"Move from Windows Phone Silverlight to UWP","pos":[32729,32771]},{"content":"Porting from XAML or Silverlight to a Universal Windows Platform app (video)","pos":[32867,32943]},{"content":"Porting an App from XAML or Silverlight to Windows 10","pos":[32962,33015]},{"content":"Porting an Xbox game to a Universal Windows Platform app","pos":[33104,33160]},{"content":"Porting from Xbox One to Windows 10 UWP","pos":[33179,33218]},{"content":"Porting from DirectX 9 to DirectX 11","pos":[33382,33418]},{"content":"Port from DirectX 9 to Universal Windows Platform (UWP)","pos":[33437,33492]},{"content":"Porting from Direct3D 11 to Direct3D 12","pos":[33579,33618]},{"content":"Porting from Direct3D 11 to Direct3D 12","pos":[33637,33676]},{"content":"Porting from OpenGL ES to Direct3D 11","pos":[33775,33812]},{"content":"Port from OpenGL ES 2.0 to Direct3D 11","pos":[33831,33869]},{"content":"OpenGL ES to Direct3D 11 using ANGLE","pos":[33951,33987]},{"content":"ANGLE","pos":[34006,34011]},{"content":"Classic Windows API equivalents in the UWP","pos":[34098,34140]},{"content":"Alternatives to Windows APIs in Universal Windows Platform (UWP) apps","pos":[34159,34228]},{"content":"Prototype and design","pos":[34317,34337]},{"content":"Now that you've decided the type of game you want to create and the tools and graphics technology you'll use to build it, you're ready to get started with the design and prototype.","pos":[34340,34520]},{"content":"At its core, your game is a Universal Windows Platform app, so that's where you'll begin.","pos":[34521,34610]},{"content":"Introduction to the Universal Windows Platform (UWP)","pos":[34616,34668]},{"content":"Windows 10 introduces the Universal Windows Platform (UWP), which provides a common API platform across Windows 10 devices.","pos":[34670,34793]},{"content":"UWP evolves and expands the Windows Runtime model and hones it into a cohesive, unified core.","pos":[34794,34887]},{"content":"Games that target the UWP can call WinRT APIs that are common to all devices.","pos":[34888,34965]},{"content":"Because the UWP provides a guaranteed core API layer, you can choose to create a single app package that will install across Windows 10 devices.","pos":[34966,35110]},{"content":"And if you want to, your game can still call APIs (including some classic Windows APIs from Win32 and .NET) that are specific to the devices your game runs on.","pos":[35111,35270]},{"content":"The goal of the UWP is to have:","pos":[35272,35303]},{"content":"One core operating system","pos":[35309,35334]},{"content":"One application platform","pos":[35339,35363]},{"content":"One gaming social network","pos":[35368,35393]},{"content":"One store","pos":[35398,35407]},{"content":"One ingestion path","pos":[35412,35430]},{"content":"The following are excellent guides that discuss the Universal Windows Platform apps in detail, and are recommended reading to help you understand the platform.","pos":[35432,35591]},{"content":"Introduction to Universal Windows Platform apps","pos":[35701,35748]},{"content":"What's a Universal Windows Platform app?","pos":[35767,35807]},{"content":"Overview of the UWP","pos":[35903,35922]},{"content":"Guide to UWP apps","pos":[35941,35958]},{"content":"Getting started with UWP development","pos":[36049,36085]},{"content":"Getting set up and ready to develop a Universal Windows Platform app is quick and easy.","pos":[36087,36174]},{"content":"The following guides take you through the process step-by-step.","pos":[36175,36238]},{"content":"Getting started with UWP development","pos":[36348,36384]},{"content":"Get started with Windows apps","pos":[36403,36432]},{"content":"Getting set up for UWP development","pos":[36506,36540]},{"content":"Get set up","pos":[36559,36569]},{"pos":[36654,37011],"content":"If you're an \"absolute beginner\" to UWP programming, and are considering using XAML in your game (see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Choosing your graphics technology and programming language<ept id=\"p1\">](#choosing_technology)</ept>), the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Windows 10 development for absolute beginners<ept id=\"p2\">](https://channel9.msdn.com/Series/Windows-10-development-for-absolute-beginners)</ept> video series is a good place to start."},{"content":"Beginners guide to Windows 10 development with XAML (Video series)","pos":[37121,37187]},{"content":"Windows 10 development for absolute beginners","pos":[37206,37251]},{"content":"Announcing the Windows 10 absolute beginners series using XAML (blog post)","pos":[37369,37443]},{"content":"Windows 10 development for absolute beginners","pos":[37462,37507]},{"content":"UWP development concepts","pos":[37635,37659]},{"content":"Overview of Universal Windows Platform app development","pos":[37769,37823]},{"content":"Develop Windows apps","pos":[37842,37862]},{"content":"Overview of network programming in the UWP","pos":[37933,37975]},{"content":"Networking and web services","pos":[37994,38021]},{"content":"Using Windows.Web.HTTP and Windows.Networking.Sockets in games","pos":[38117,38179]},{"content":"Networking for games","pos":[38198,38218]},{"content":"Asynchronous programming concepts in the UWP","pos":[38302,38346]},{"content":"Asynchronous programming","pos":[38365,38389]},{"content":"Process lifetime management","pos":[38480,38507]},{"content":"Process lifetime management, or app lifecyle, describes the various activation states that a Universal Windows Platform app can transition through.","pos":[38509,38656]},{"content":"Your game can be activated, suspended, resumed, or terminated, and can transition through those states in a variety of ways.","pos":[38657,38781]},{"content":"Handling app lifecyle transitions","pos":[38891,38924]},{"content":"App lifecycle","pos":[38943,38956]},{"content":"Using Microsoft Visual Studio to trigger app transitions","pos":[39052,39108]},{"content":"How to trigger suspend, resume, and background events for Windows Store apps in Visual Studio","pos":[39127,39220]},{"content":"Designing game UX","pos":[39303,39320]},{"content":"The genesis of a great game is inspired design.","pos":[39322,39369]},{"content":"Games share some common user interface elements and design principles with apps, but games often have a unique look, feel, and design goal for their user experience.","pos":[39371,39536]},{"content":"Games succeed when thoughtful design is applied to both aspects—when should your game use tested UX, and when should it diverge and innovate?","pos":[39537,39678]},{"content":"The presentation technology that you choose for your game—DirectX, XAML, HTML5, or some combination of the three—will influence implementation details, but the design principles you apply are largely independent of that choice.","pos":[39679,39906]},{"content":"Separately from UX design, gameplay design such as level design, pacing, world design, and other aspects is an art form of its own—one that's up to you and your team, and not covered in this development guide.","pos":[39908,40117]},{"content":"UWP design basics and guidelines","pos":[40227,40259]},{"content":"Designing UWP apps","pos":[40278,40296]},{"content":"Designing for app lifecycle states","pos":[40366,40400]},{"content":"UX guidelines for launch, suspend, and resume","pos":[40419,40464]},{"content":"Targeting multiple device form factors (video)","pos":[40560,40606]},{"content":"Designing Games for a Windows Core World","pos":[40625,40665]},{"content":"Color guideline and palette","pos":[40785,40812]},{"content":"Following a consistent color guideline in your game improves aesthetics, aids navigation, and is a powerful tool to inform the player of menu and HUD functionality.","pos":[40814,40978]},{"content":"Consistent coloring of game elements like warnings, damage, XP, and achievements can lead to cleaner UI and reduce the need for explicit labels.","pos":[40979,41123]},{"content":"Color guide","pos":[41233,41244]},{"content":"Best Practices: Color","pos":[41263,41284]},{"content":"Typography","pos":[41440,41450]},{"content":"The appropriate use of typography enhances many aspects of your game, including UI layout, navigation, readability, atmosphere, brand, and player immersion.","pos":[41452,41608]},{"content":"Typography guide","pos":[41718,41734]},{"content":"Best Practices: Typography","pos":[41753,41779]},{"content":"UI map","pos":[41859,41865]},{"content":"A UI map is a layout of game navigation and menus expressed as a flowchart.","pos":[41867,41942]},{"content":"The UI map helps all involved stakeholders understand the game’s interface and navigation paths, and can expose potential roadblocks and dead ends early in the development cycle.","pos":[41943,42121]},{"content":"UI map guide","pos":[42231,42243]},{"content":"Best Practices: UI Map","pos":[42262,42284]},{"content":"DirectX development","pos":[42364,42383]},{"content":"DirectX game development on the UWP","pos":[42493,42528]},{"content":"Games and DirectX","pos":[42547,42564]},{"content":"DirectX interaction with the UWP app model","pos":[42612,42654]},{"content":"The app object and DirectX","pos":[42673,42699]},{"content":"DirectX overviews and reference","pos":[42790,42821]},{"content":"DirectX Graphics and Gaming","pos":[42840,42867]},{"content":"Direct3D 12 programming guide and reference","pos":[42966,43009]},{"content":"Direct3D 12 Graphics","pos":[43028,43048]},{"content":"DirectX 12 fundamentals (video)","pos":[43147,43178]},{"content":"Better Power, Better Performance: Your Game on DirectX 12","pos":[43197,43254]},{"content":"The DirectX Tool Kit, DirectX texture processing library, and DirectXMesh geometry processing library provide texture, mesh, sprite, and other utility functionality and helper classes for DirectX development.","pos":[43384,43592]},{"content":"These libraries can save a lot of time and effort compared to implementing these features yourself.","pos":[43593,43692]},{"content":"Though implemented primarily for Direct3D 11, some portions of these libraries also work in Direct3D 12.","pos":[43693,43797]},{"content":"Get the DirectX Tool Kit (DirectX 11)","pos":[43907,43944]},{"content":"DirectXTK","pos":[43963,43972]},{"content":"Get the DirectX texture processing library (DirectX 11)","pos":[44057,44112]},{"content":"DirectXTex","pos":[44131,44141]},{"content":"Get the DirectXMesh geometry processing library","pos":[44226,44273]},{"content":"DirectXMesh","pos":[44292,44303]},{"content":"Direct3D 12 support in the DirectXTK (blog post)","pos":[44388,44436]},{"content":"Support for DirectX 12","pos":[44455,44477]},{"content":"Production","pos":[44557,44567]},{"content":"Your studio is now fully engaged and moving into the production cycle, with work distributed throughout your team.","pos":[44570,44684]},{"content":"You're polishing, refactoring, and extending the prototype to craft it into a full game.","pos":[44685,44773]},{"content":"Notifications and live tiles","pos":[44779,44807]},{"content":"A tile is your game's representation on the Start Menu.","pos":[44809,44864]},{"content":"Tiles and notifications can drive player interest even when they aren't currently playing your game.","pos":[44865,44965]},{"content":"Developing tiles and badges","pos":[45075,45102]},{"content":"Tiles, badges, and notifications","pos":[45121,45153]},{"content":"Sample illustrating live tiles and notifications","pos":[45249,45297]},{"content":"Notifications sample","pos":[45316,45336]},{"content":"Adaptive tile templates (blog post)","pos":[45464,45499]},{"content":"Adaptive Tile Templates - Schema and Documentation","pos":[45518,45568]},{"content":"Designing tiles and badges","pos":[45721,45747]},{"content":"Guidelines for tiles and badges","pos":[45766,45797]},{"content":"Windows 10 app for interactively developing live tile templates","pos":[45893,45956]},{"content":"Notifications Visualizer","pos":[45975,45999]},{"content":"Enable in-app product (IAP) purchases","pos":[46083,46120]},{"content":"An IAP (in-app product) is a supplementary item that players can purchase in-game.","pos":[46122,46204]},{"content":"IAPs can be new add-ons, game levels, items, or anything else that your players might enjoy.","pos":[46205,46297]},{"content":"Used appropriately, IAPs can provide revenue while improving the game experience.","pos":[46298,46379]},{"content":"You define and publish your game's IAPs through the Windows Dev Center dashboard, and enable in-app purchases in your game's code.","pos":[46380,46510]},{"content":"Durable in-app products","pos":[46620,46643]},{"content":"Enable in-app product purchases","pos":[46662,46693]},{"content":"Consumable in-app products","pos":[46789,46815]},{"content":"Enable consumable in-app product purchases","pos":[46834,46876]},{"content":"In-app product details and submission","pos":[46972,47009]},{"content":"IAP submissions","pos":[47028,47043]},{"content":"Monitor IAP sales and demographics for your game","pos":[47139,47187]},{"content":"IAP acquisitions report","pos":[47206,47229]},{"content":"Debugging and performance monitoring tools","pos":[47319,47361]},{"content":"The Windows Performance Toolkit (WPT) consists of performance monitoring tools that produce in-depth performance profiles of Windows operating systems and applications.","pos":[47363,47531]},{"content":"This is especially useful for monitoring memory usage and improving game performance.","pos":[47532,47617]},{"content":"The Windows Performance Toolkit is included in the Windows 10 SDK and Windows ADK.","pos":[47618,47700]},{"content":"This toolkit consists of two independent tools: Windows Performance Recorder (WPR) and Windows Performance Analyzer (WPA).","pos":[47701,47823]},{"content":"Another useful tool for generating dump files to investigate game crashes is ProcDump, which is part of <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Windows Sysinternals<ept id=\"p1\">](https://technet.microsoft.com/sysinternals/default)</ept>.","pos":[47824,48003]},{"content":"Get Windows Performance Toolkit (WPT) from Windows 10 SDK","pos":[48113,48170]},{"content":"Windows 10 SDK","pos":[48189,48203]},{"content":"Get Windows Performance Toolkit (WPT) from Windows ADK","pos":[48307,48361]},{"content":"Windows ADK","pos":[48380,48391]},{"content":"Troubleshoot unresponsible UI using Windows Performance Analyzer (video)","pos":[48488,48560]},{"content":"Critical path analysis with WPA","pos":[48579,48610]},{"content":"Diagnose memory usage and leaks using Windows Performance Recorder (video)","pos":[48768,48842]},{"content":"Memory footprint and leaks","pos":[48861,48887]},{"content":"Get ProcDump","pos":[49015,49027]},{"content":"ProcDump","pos":[49046,49054]},{"content":"Learn to use ProcDump (video)","pos":[49145,49174]},{"content":"Configure ProcDump to create dump files","pos":[49193,49232]},{"content":"Advanced DirectX techniques and concepts","pos":[49341,49381]},{"content":"Some portions of DirectX development can be nuanced and complex.","pos":[49383,49447]},{"content":"When you get to the point in production where you need to dig down into the details of your DirectX engine, or debug difficult performance problems, the resources and information in this section can help.","pos":[49448,49652]},{"content":"Optimizing graphics and performance (video)","pos":[49762,49805]},{"content":"Advanced DirectX 12 Graphics and Performance","pos":[49824,49868]},{"content":"DirectX graphics debugging (video)","pos":[49996,50030]},{"content":"Solve the Tough Graphics Problems with Your Game Using DirectX Tools","pos":[50049,50117]},{"content":"Direct3D 12 programming guide","pos":[50270,50299]},{"content":"Direct3D 12 Programming Guide","pos":[50318,50347]},{"content":"Combining DirectX and XAML","pos":[50446,50472]},{"content":"DirectX and XAML interop","pos":[50491,50515]},{"content":"The Microsoft DirectX product team has produced a series of in-depth videos about DirectX 12 development.","pos":[50573,50678]},{"content":"They cover the details of resource binding, presentation modes, debugging, resource barriers, and many other DirectX 12 concepts.","pos":[50679,50808]},{"content":"This series also occasionally features guest presenters.","pos":[50809,50865]},{"content":"Graphics and DirectX 12 development videos (YouTube channel)","pos":[50975,51035]},{"content":"Microsoft DirectX 12 and Graphics Education","pos":[51054,51097]},{"content":"Direct3D 12 resource and heap management (video)","pos":[51193,51241]},{"content":"Heaps and Resources in DirectX 12","pos":[51260,51293]},{"content":"Globalization and localization","pos":[51384,51414]},{"content":"Develop world-ready games for the Windows platform and learn about the international features built into Microsoft’s top products.","pos":[51416,51546]},{"content":"Preparing your game for the global market","pos":[51656,51697]},{"content":"Guidelines when developing for a global audience","pos":[51716,51764]},{"content":"Bridging languages, cultures, and technology","pos":[51870,51914]},{"content":"Online resource for language conventions and standard Microsoft terminology","pos":[51933,52008]},{"content":"Submitting and publishing your game","pos":[52087,52122]},{"content":"The following guides and information help make the publishing and submission process as smooth as possible.","pos":[52125,52232]},{"content":"Packaging and uploading","pos":[52238,52261]},{"content":"You'll use the new unified Windows Dev Center dashboard to publish and manage your game packages.","po